Welcome new #RailStrong staff member Caitlyn Wood, Kindergarten Teacher for the Proctor School District!ğŸ‘ ğŸ’šğŸ–¤ğŸš‚

Caitlyn graduated from Graceland University and is from Jackson, Tennessee. She moved up here around six years ago after graduating from college. She has five siblings, three nieces, and two nephews. She is married to her wonderful husband, Anthony Wood, and they have three fur babies.

Caitlyn enjoys kayaking, taking the dogs to the lake, coaching soccer for Gith and LSC women's team, visiting Gooseberry Falls, and gardening.

"I hope to share some new perspectives and ideas as well as gain new perspectives and ideas from the Proctor School District community."

post_text:
Welcome new #RailStrong staff member Michael Bauman, Elementary Music and General Music Teacher for the Proctor School District!ğŸ‘ ğŸ’šğŸ–¤ğŸš‚

Michael graduated from Hermantown High School and then went on to receive a Bachelor of Arts degree in Music Education at the College of St. Scholastica.

Michael is the oldest of three children and grew up in Hermantown. His parents were both educators and musicians, so music teaching is in his blood. He enjoys being outside and loves the fresh air! He loves to fish, run, walk, hike, mountain bike, disc golf, you name it! As long as he can spend time outside, life is good.

"I am looking forward to joining your community and sharing with your children the love of music. Music is a life long journey, so let's start today!"

Let's give a #RailStrong shout-out to John Werner who earned Academic All-State honors for the third year in a row!

To earn this honor John had to qualify based on his GPA and run a certain standard set by the MN State Track and Field Coaches Association. The minimum GPA to qualify is 3.6. John was over this GPA requirement. He also had to run below a 2:06 in the 800m of his main event.

Mrs. Gross' 4th graders at Pike Lake are discussing how colors used in artwork can make the viewer feel a certain way, just like words in text.

Can you conclude how our #RailStrong students are feeling about our Minnesota winter? ğŸ¤”â„ï¸ğŸ’šğŸ–¤

post_text:
#RailStrong fourth graders at Pike Lake are using the art form of Tableau which means, "a living picture' to show their understanding of new vocabulary words.

This type of art form is a part of the Arts Integration approach to teaching in which students construct and demonstrate understanding through an art form. Students engage in a creative process that connects an art form and another subject area and meets evolving objectives in both.

Students work in small groups to physically demonstrate a word or concept. They only have one minute! This requires the use of all the skills they have been building; body, voice, imagination, concentration, and cooperation.

post_text:
Proctor High School Students had some incredible Pathways experiences last week taking part in the Construct Tomorrow event at the DECC and traveling to the Nursing Department at St. Scholastica.

With Construct Tomorrow, students were able to meet with representatives from apprenticeship programs in the area and actually try the work they would do in that field!

At St. Scholastica, students partnered with faculty and students to participate in simulations where they helped deliver a baby, performed a health assessment and took part in a virtual reality experience.

A huge thanks to all who made these hands-on experiences possible for our #RailStrong students!ğŸš‚ğŸ’šğŸ–¤
